{
    "docId": "case_study_brief_v1",
    "metadata": {
        "source": "case_study_brief",
        "type": "project_context"
    },
    "content": "This document outlines the objective, core logic, deliverables, and scoring for the take-home project. Objective Your mission is to build a backend service that automates the initial screening of a job application. The service will receive a candidate's CV and a project report, evaluate them against a specific job description and a case study brief, and produce a structured, AI-generated evaluation report. Core Logic & Data Flow The system operates with a clear separation of inputs and reference documents: Candidate-Provided Inputs (The Data to be Evaluated): Candidate CV: The candidate's resume (PDF). Project Report: The candidate's project report to our take-home case study (PDF). System-Internal Documents (The 'Ground Truth' for Comparison): Job Description: A document detailing the requirements and responsibilities for the role you're currently applying. This will be used as ground truth for the Candidate CV. Case Study Brief: This document. Used as ground truth for the Project Report (PDF). Scoring Rubric: A predefined set of parameters for evaluating CV and Report, each has its own documents (PDF). Deliverables 1. Backend Service (API endpoints) Implement a backend service with at least the following RESTful API endpoints: POST /upload: Accepts multipart/form-data containing the Candidate CV and Project Report (PDF). Stores files and returns each with its own ID for later processing. POST /evaluate: Triggers the asynchronous AI evaluation pipeline. Receives input job title (string) and both document IDs. Immediately returns a job ID to track the evaluation process (e.g., {\"id\": \"456\", \"status\": \"queued\"}). GET /result/{id}: Retrieves the status and result of an evaluation job. Should reflect the asynchronous, multi-stage nature of the process. While queued or processing: returns {\"id\": \"456\", \"status\": \"queued\" | \"processing\"}. Once completed: returns a structured JSON including id, status: \"completed\", and a result object containing cv_match_rate, cv_feedback, project_score, project_feedback, and overall_summary. 2. Evaluation Pipeline The AI-driven pipeline, triggered by POST /evaluate, should consist of these key components: RAG (Context Retrieval): Ingest all System-Internal Documents (Job Description, Case Study Brief, Both Scoring Rubrics) into a vector database. Retrieve relevant sections and inject into prompts. Prompt Design & LLM Chaining: CV Evaluation: Parse CV, retrieve from Job Description and CV Scoring Rubrics, use an LLM to get cv_match_rate & cv_feedback. Project Report Evaluation: Parse Project Report, retrieve from Case Study Brief and CV Scoring Rubrics, use an LLM to get project_score & project_feedback. Final Analysis: Use a final LLM call to synthesize the outputs into a concise overall_summary. Long-Running Process Handling: POST /evaluate must not block. Store task, return job ID, allow GET /result/{id} to check periodically. Error Handling & Randomness Control: Simulate edge cases and how the service handles them. Simulate LLM API failures (timeouts, rate limit) and implement retries/back-off. Control LLM temperature or add a validation layer to keep responses stable. 3. Standardized Evaluation Parameters Define at least these scoring parameters: CV Evaluation (Match Rate): Technical Skills Match (backend, databases, APIs, cloud, AI/LLM exposure), Experience Level (years, project complexity), Relevant Achievements (impact, scale), Cultural Fit (communication, learning attitude). Project Deliverable Evaluation: Correctness (meets requirements: prompt design, chaining, RAG, handling errors), Code Quality (clean, modular, testable), Resilience (handles failures, retries), Documentation (clear README, explanation of trade-offs), Creativity / Bonus (optional improvements like authentication, deployment, dashboards). Each parameter can be scored 1-5, then aggregated to final score."
}

